page.title: 11Landscape
page.content: The landscape in our area is typical of many coastal plains, as a result of industrialisation and the growth of a major port it has become densely populated. The land does not rise over 50 feet above sea level,the skyline being broken by pylons, factories, blocks of flats and dockland with recently constructed roadways and flyovers, giving the view of modern development. In the south the landscape is more intensely covered with office buildings,intermingled with private dwellings,while the north east and western sections have more open spaces ie.playing fields,allotments,a golf course and a brook which for most part runs underground.It is bordered to the east by the Leeds and Liverpool Canal. Buildings of note are Walton Prison, National Giro and Crosby Town Hall.
